Removing Outliers¶

In [67]:
#IQR method for outliers removels we can't use it in our case . 
#In our cas there's no outliers 
def remove_ouliers(a):
    print(f"size of dataset before removing outliers : {dataset_b.shape}")
    print(dataset_b[a].describe())
    # Scatter plot (before removing outliers)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))  
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)  
    sns.distplot(dataset_b[a])
    plt.title(f"Before {a} - distplot ")

    # Boxplot (before removing outliers)
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)  
    plt.boxplot([dataset_b[a]], labels=["Before"])
    plt.title(f"Before {a} - Box Plot")
    

    # Calculate IQR and identify outliers
    q25, q75 = np.percentile(a=dataset_b[a], q=[25, 75])
    IQR = q75 - q25
    lower_limit = q25 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_limit = q75 + 1.5 * IQR
    
    
    dataset_b.drop(dataset_b[dataset_b[a] > upper_limit].index, inplace=True)
    dataset_b.drop(dataset_b[dataset_b[a] < lower_limit].index, inplace=True)
    
    print(lower_limit)
    print(upper_limit)
    # Scatter plot (after removing outliers)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))  
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)  
    sns.distplot(dataset_b[a])
    plt.title(f"After {a} - distplot ")

    # Boxplot (after removing outliers)
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)  
    plt.boxplot([dataset_b[a]], labels=["After"])
    plt.title(f"After {a} - Box Plot")
    print(f"size of dataset after removing outliers : {dataset_b.shape}")
    plt.show()

plt.colorbar()

plt.title('Pairwise Correlation Matrix')

    for j in range(len(correlation_array[0])):
        plt.text(j, i, f"{correlation_array[i][j]:.2f}", ha="center", va="center", color="black")

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assume you have trained a RandomForestClassifier and assigned it to 'rfc'

# Calculate permutation importances
perm_importance = permutation_importance(model_svm, X_test, y_test, n_repeats=30, random_state=42)

# Get feature importances
feature_importances = perm_importance.importances_mean

# Extract feature names from the DataFrame
feature_names = features_b_.columns

# Optionally, plot the feature importances
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(range(len(features_b_.columns)), feature_importances, tick_label=feature_names)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Importance')
plt.xticks(rotation=25, ha='right')  # Rotate x-axis labels 45 degrees

plt.title('SVM Permutation Importance of Features')

# Annotate the bars with the importance values
for i, v in enumerate(feature_importances):
    plt.text(i, v + 0.006, f'{v:.4f}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In [193]:
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

    
# Define hyperparameter combinations
hidden_layer_sizes = [(7, 7),(10, 10), (15, 15), (20, 20)]
learning_rate_init = [0.01,0.03,0.05, 0.09, 0.1,0.3]

best_score = 0
best_params = None

for layers in hidden_layer_sizes:
    for rate in learning_rate_init:
        mlp = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes=layers, learning_rate_init=rate, random_state=0)
        mlp.out_activation_ = 'sigmoid'
        mlp.n_layers_=8
        score = cross_val_score(mlp, features_b, category_b, cv=kf, scoring="accuracy")
        avg_score = score.mean()
        if avg_score > best_score:
            best_score = avg_score
            best_params = {'hidden_layer_sizes': layers, 'learning_rate_init': rate}

print(f"Best score: {best_score:.3f} with params: {best_params}")

In [205]:
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB


    
# Define smoothing values to try
smoothing_values = np.logspace(-9, 0, num=10)

best_score = 0
best_smoothing = None

# Loop through smoothing values
for smoothing in smoothing_values:
    nb = GaussianNB(var_smoothing=smoothing)  # Set smoothing for each iteration
    score = cross_val_score(nb, features_b, category_b, cv=kf, scoring="accuracy")
    avg_score = score.mean()
    if avg_score > best_score:
        best_score = avg_score
        best_smoothing = smoothing

print(f"Best score: {best_score:.3f} with var_smoothing: {best_smoothing:.3e}")

pyplot.plot(lr_fpr3, lr_tpr3,  color='purple' , label='ROC RF (area = %0.2f)' % lr_auc3)
pyplot.plot(lr_fpr2, lr_tpr2,  color='green' , label='ROC MLP (area = %0.2f)' % lr_auc2)

pyplot.plot(lr_fpr4, lr_tpr4,  color='red' , label='ROC SVM (area = %0.2f)' % lr_auc4)

pyplot.plot(lr_fpr1, lr_tpr1,  color='black' , label='ROC LR (area = %0.2f)' % lr_auc1)

pyplot.plot(lr_fpr, lr_tpr,  color='darkorange' , label='ROC NB (area = %0.2f)' % lr_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', linestyle='--' , label='Random classifier ')

# axis labels
pyplot.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
pyplot.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
# show the legend
pyplot.legend()
# show the plot
pyplot.show()
